<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>_x0001_</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:18pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence by Dairy Crest</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Dairy Crest – an Overview</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The dairy sector is one of the largest food market categories in the UK worth £10bn</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Dairy Crest is the leading British owned dairy company. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We are now the only UK listed dairy business and the only major liquid milk processor predominantly in British ownership.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Dairy Crest is one of the UK's largest purchasers of fresh milk, buying circa. 2 billion litres every year.  We </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">mainly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">source our milk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> directly from dairy farmers with 75% coming from farmer suppliers wh</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o are contracted to Dairy Crest - as well as milk co-operatives and brokers.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The state of dairy farming in UK</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Parts of the UK have amongst the best natural conditions in the world for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">dairy farming with lush grass, rolling hills and a relatively small human population.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We also have an excellent tradition of animal husbandry and some exceptional dairy farmers - the skills which have been passed down the generations, showcased in our exce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">llent dairy products, including top quality cheese and milk.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The dairy sector has always made up a significant section of the British rural economy with dairy forming 17 per cent of the agricultural output of the UK as a whole.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Dairy farming provides the f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">oundation for large parts of the rural economy. Drivers are employed from the local area to collect the raw milk from farmers supplying Dairy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Crest;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> these vehicles use local garages for servicing. The drivers further support the local economy through using</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> local services and shops. This demonstrates the fine balance within the rural economy. The implications for the wider rural economy if dairy farming continues to decline are severe.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the shape of the dairy sector in this country is changing, with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the number of dairy farmers in the sector dropping. In fact, in the past ten years, the number of dairy farmers in England and Wales has fallen by 43%. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(Source: Defra, DARD, SEERAD.) This rate has slowed down - the number of UK dairy farms fell at a slower</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> rate in 2012 than in 2011 but it is still dropping. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Steep rises in the cost of production and dramatic cuts in profit for the whole supply chain – farmers, processors and retailers alike have contributed to this decline.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Securing a future for the dairy s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ector</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Dairy Crest believes that there are a number of different measures that can - and must - be taken to secure</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the future of the dairy sector</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Firstly, every effort must be made to drive fairness in the voluntary code of practice for milk processors, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">which was signed on 31 August 2012.  This means ensuring contract terms allowing farmers to move their milk supply following a milk price reduction and giving farmers longer notice of any price changes should be the same for all processors, including co-op</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">erative models.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Secondly, Dairy Crest would like to see more farmers and processors moving to a transparent pricing formula which will continue to build trust betwe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">en farmers and the processors. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Thirdly, it is essential that the entire supply chain works </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">more closely together and that there is continued support from the retailers and other “large end users”, such as coffee shop chains.  We hope that by discussing with them the issues which affect milk price, such as commodity price increases, ensuring they</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are aware of the pressure on farmers and the whole dairy sector, we can avoid the sort</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of crisis that hit last year. A fair pricing system should recognise the bargaining power that different parts of the supply chain have.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold">How best to improve UK (and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold">EU) food security, including using resources more efficiently;</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Supply Chain working together</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">To ensure the long-term future of the British dairy sector, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">need to engage all elements of the supply chain and we work hard to build relationships with our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">supplying farmers and the wider farming community.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Crucial to this, is our relationship with Dairy Crest Direct (DCD), the Producer Organisation (PO) which all of our supplying farmers are members of. This is an independent farmer PO, established in May 20</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">04. T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> structure allows us to work together on improving </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">efficiency in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">our supply chain.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Dairy Crest would like to see all Producer Organisations (PO) making a positive contribution to the supply chain. We believe that collaboration between relevant parti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">es will be key to delivering value for both individual business/s and for the UK dairy sector as a whole.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">A Voluntary Code of Practice which </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">fairly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">governs the whole sector</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Dairy Crest was the first processor to sign up to the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Voluntary Code of Practice (VCO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">P) in 2012 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">since when</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> we have been committed to the code in full. Indeed, we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have amended</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> all of our farmer contracts to reflect these principles</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, including two of the key elements relating</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to notice period for a price chang</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e and the ability for a farmer to resign with 3 months’ notice if they do not agree to a price change.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">not all</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> processors </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have reflected</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> these principles in the code </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in their contracts and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for the VCO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">P to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">work;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">now </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">need to ensure that all proc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">essors and supplier</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are afforded parity in terms.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Make s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">upply chain</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> efficient and cost effective</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For any supply chain to be completely sustainable, it must be possible for all those involved to make sufficient returns to reinves</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t regularly in their </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">businesses and attract the next generation into the sector.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">One of the big issues for dairy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">farmers over recent years</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> has been the insecurity of their returns and the lack of predictability. This has dissuaded prosp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ective investors or banks from putting ca</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">pital behind the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">business</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">es</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to modernise or expand, a real problem for many of our suppliers. Given the financial climate of the past few years, this has been exacerb</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ated</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Making dairy commercial</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">For the dairy industry to be sustainable, we need to make</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> sure that it is a vibrant market place where companies can grow and invest. Farmers and companies must be encouraged and helped to innovate around new product development (NPD) and expand businesses where possible.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Dairy companies and retailers must commu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nicate better with the public so they know why it matters to buy British and to buy British dairy products.  We </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have to help them to make the right decisions when they go into the supermarket.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Processors must add value to the milk they buy by creating new </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">brands and new products.  For instance, in Dairy Crest we are very proud of our Cathedral City cheese.  And we continually innovate – last year we introduced </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Chedds</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for kids, this year we introduced a selection of small blocks of our cheeses in a handy bag</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  This is our responsibility to our business and to our farmers. When we do have successful brands we share the benefits with farmers who supply the milk – no ifs, no buts!</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is also our responsibility to invest in our creameries and factories and to do </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">this without passing the cost back down the line to the farmers, which is a principle that matters a great deal to us in Dairy Crest.  </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold">The relationship between the price of food and the cost of producing it;</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">To answer this question, it is worth looking </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">closer at the recent milk price crisis where the relationship between the price of food and the cost of producing it broke down to the great detriment of the UK dairy sector.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2012 Mil</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">k Price Crisis – what </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">happened?</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2012 was a difficult year for British dai</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ry farmers, many of whom</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> had the profitability of their businesses hit hard. The hardship caused to dairy farmers was severe.  It is worth jus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t examining how it came about. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In 2010, the commodity markets for cream dramatically dropped, with prices reachin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">g record lows at the end of 2010 and staying there. Dairy Crest had to absorb a 4p drop in the value of every litre of milk it purchased. Normally the cream market p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">icks up after Christmas but that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> year it did not happen. Eventually, we had no option but t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o cut the farm-gate price by 2 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ppl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">; this was announced in May </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2012 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">with immediate effect.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This was a hugely difficult decision which we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">could not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> avoid taking. Our dairies business has a turnover of over £1 billion, but a profit of just £10 million in 2010</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">/11- £5 million of that from selling off property. We could no longer absorb the losses that we were accruing, not least because to ensure a long-term future for our business and the UK dairy sector, we need to continue to invest in our farmers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, in marketi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ng </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sites and we cannot do so on such a small margin.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">On reflection and having talked to our farmer representatives, we realised that the immediacy of the milk price cuts put our farmers in a very difficult position.  They needed more warning.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">That is why we decided not to wait until the new voluntary code of practice was agreed within the whole sector, but to implement it immediately so that in future our farmers would be given a month’s notice of any change in the price they received for their</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> milk and would find it easier to switch their supply contract should they wish to do so.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">At the same time, we held meetings with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Alun</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Davies AM, the Deputy Farming Minister in Wales as well as Sir Jim </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Paice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> MP, the-then Farming Minister to ensure they w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ere aware of our decision and our anxieties for the impact it would have on our farmers.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In July, as the commodity markets remained stubbornly low we again decided to cut prices in August, but reversed this decision when it was clear that the hardship to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> farmers caused by poor weather and steeply increasing annual feed costs was unsustainable. This put additional pressure on the profitability of our dairies business.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In September, as the commodity prices rose, supported by some but not all customers, we r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">aised our farm-gate milk price so that farmers were being paid more than before the May cut.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We are now paying record milk prices, having increased our sta</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ndard liquid milk price five</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> times since last year. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is our hope that this will help farmers who </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are struggling with rising feed and fuel costs.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Mathematical Formula</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> – the way forward</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">At the moment, the vast majority of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">farm gate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> milk prices are calculated through monthly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">negotiations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> with farmer representative bodies and the processors. This does not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> allow for long term investment from either side.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This year, Dairy Crest became the first processor to offer our farmers on a standard liquid contract, the opportunity to move to a formula milk price from 1 April 2013. This was in line with the principles </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of the Voluntary Code of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Practice and Muller Wiseman has</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> since launched a similar arrangement.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This is in line with our commitment in to transparency and comes following a review of our milk pricing mechanism in conjunction with DCD. As part of this proces</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s, last year, we jointly appointed the independent consultant, Stephen Bradley, a well-known and respected figure within the dairy sector, to help us develop and agree a pricing formula.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our joint aim has been to find a more predictable formulaic way of ag</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reeing our DC milk prices to help stabilise the sector and so help to return some </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">confidence to British dairy farmers The process we have been through with Stephen has been very thorough</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and the formula has acted in the way it was intended to since then, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.e.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> following global commodity market trends.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We would like to see this type of system more widely used to encourage more stability and hence long term investment in the sector.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold">The implications of volatility in global food supply and demand for UK food</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold"> security;</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Adding value through growing brands</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The best way to take away global commodity risks (such as the fluctuations in cream which had such a devastating effect last year), is for the sector to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">focus on adding value </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to the supply chain.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Dairy Crest h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">as a good h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">istory of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> doing this through growing market leading positions with brands such as Cathedral City, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">FR</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ijj</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, Country Life and Clover.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Cathedral City – a virtuous circle</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This is best evidenced with farmers in the South West, who supply our cheese </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">business. We buy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> milk from 265 farms in Cornwall and 135 in Devon, with an average herd size of around 170 cows.   This is one of the largest and most dense milk fields in the UK.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Davidstow</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, we have created a ‘virtuous circle’ - milk from one of the bes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t milk fields in the world is turned into very popular cheeses in a well invested, world-class creamery, sold as leading brands, allowing it to pay a premium for the milk, which encourages further investment by the farmers in their farms and so in the milk</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> field.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">On average, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Davidstow</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> farmers have received a premium of 1.3 pence per litre (around 5 per cent) for their milk over the last five years and the price today is above 32 pence per litre.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Forward looking Investment at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Davidstow</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Going forward, we hav</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e also recently announced a £45 million investment to make de-mineralised whey powder from the whey which comes off from the cheese making process at our plant in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Davidstow</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, Cornwall.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This powder is the base ingredient of baby food and will add </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">further </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">val</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ue to our milk stream. </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold">The potential value and contribution of science and GM technology to UK food security.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">New Product Development </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">To keep ahead in branded markets we need to use science and NPD to develop, diversify and grow </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">our brands</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. For </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">instance, we have invested in research and development for a Cathedral City spreadable product which will allow us to meet new markets and consumers.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This further secures the future for our South Western farmers who are on our cheese contracts, ensures tha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t they are still paid a premium for their milk and will allow us to continue to expand our cheese business.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold">How food and farming supply chains, and the current systems for traceability, can contribute to increased resilience;</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Dairy Crest – a reliable and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">sustainable British supply chain</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This year has seen unprecedented consumer interest in provenance and supply chains due to the focus this January on horsemeat.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">At Dairy Crest, we only buy British milk from British farmers. Our farmers are proud of their he</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ritage and we believe this provenance has a huge role to play in the quality of their milk</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We current</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ly have a dairy deficit of 100,000</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> tonnes of cheese in this country. So, whilst we are looking to increase our added value sales abroad and internationally</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, we must also continue to focus on addressing the dairy deficit we still have in this country.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Supporting British dairy farmers</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Dairy Crest would like to see the Government supporting the British dairy industry and British dairy farmers by encouraging peo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ple to buy fresh, healthy, natural British dairy products whenever possible.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This should include</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">labelling system which seeks to encourage, inform and help consumers. A system which promotes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">informed choice as well as recognising the health benefits of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">dairy products and does not suppress demand.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Count</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">ry of Origin Labelling – Cheese</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Consumers are increasingly making purchasing decisions based on the provenance of the product.  They want a labelling system which is open, transparent and trustworthy.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Dairy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Crest has made a commitment to follow DEFRA guidance on country of origin labelling for milk, cheese, cream and butter. We label the country of origin as that of the milk or, for cheese and butter, where the curd manufacture or churning takes place.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">But a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t the moment, cheese made in Ireland with Irish milk is being labelled as British because it is packed in the UK.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Currently, in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> most retailers, their own brand cheese which is marked with a Union flag, will be made from Irish milk.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This is a real danger to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> British dairy farmers. With the abolition of EU milk quotas in 2015, we are expecting cheese production in ROI to increase significantly which could make the situation even worse.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold">Whether climate change risks are adequately incorporated in UK food security strategies and planning; </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Climate Change</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In the short term the dairy sector is vulnerable to its high dependency on energy through production costs.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Adverse global weather </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">conditions were also behind feed price increases in 2012, as supply was reduced. The price of feed wheat rose by £20/tonne (11.6%) and the price of intensive energy dairy rations rose £26/tonne (11.0%). (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DairyCo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Source: ©FARM BRIEF, AHDB/HGCA</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) Looking ahe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ad, this could become a big issue for farmers and the whole sector.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The dairy industry is aware that climate change is important and Dairy Crest has contributed to Dairy UK’s Milk Roadmap that has set industry targets.  We have been working with our farmer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> suppliers to comply with these targets.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The dairy sector is proactive on combating climate change. Dairy Crest has contributed to and complied with the Dairy Roadmap that has set ambitious targets for the amount of recycled plastic used in bottles, energy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and CO2 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">emissions. We have also been working with our farmers to help them comply with these targets.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold">The obstacles facing food producers, including small farmers, seeking to increase production and access new markets; </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What are the major </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">threats/opportunities to UK milk processors?</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Major Threats</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Sustainable milk supply</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Cheap imports</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Consumers under increasing financial pressure</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">bTB</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> &amp; animal diseases</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Misleading public health messages </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; orphans:0; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Major Opportunities</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Import substitution – increase our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">share of the domestic market</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; orphans:0; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">More consumer focus on trusted farm standards and provenance</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Dairy Crest’s export strategy</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Dairy Crest exports our market-leading brands into a number of markets. Cathedral City, in particular, has seen strong volume growth in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Germany, Russia, France and Benelux in particular. We were really pleased to be listed in South Africa recently and will continue to target growth in these markets.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A key focus of Dairy Crest’s business remains shoring up the domestic cheese market. At th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e moment, we are still importing nearly 100, 000t of our Cheddar from outside the UK. Dairy Crest would like to take back some of this market </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">by continuing to grow </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">our top-quality branded cheeses, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Davidstow</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and Cathedral City. Cathedral City in particular </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">already enjoys significant market share but over the next few years, we will aim to increase this through our proven track record with New Product Development and marketing. To do this, we need a growing supply of milk in Cornwall and Devon.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">£45 millio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">n investment at our creamery in Cornwall, will allow us to target the growing Chinese infant formula market by removing minerals from the whey to produce demineralised whey powder, a base ingredient for baby food. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As well as leading calls for the Governme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nt to help support the British dairy sector by making sure that there is honest and clear country of origin labelling on all cheese coming into the country, we </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are also actively growing our export business; Cathedral City is now available throughout Europe</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, as well as in Russia, South Korea, the USA and many other parts of the world. We continue to work closely with Defra and UKTI to explore further exporting opportunities abroad.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Bringing the next generation through</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In 1993 there were 37,456 dairy farmers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in the UK. Now there are 14,549. We need to address this as a sector and ensure we are providing a long term career option for people throughout the industry.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Dairy Crest is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> a long-term supporter of initiatives to encourage and support the next generation </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of dairy farmers and are proud to sponsor the Dairy Crest/RABDF Student Award and the Dairy Crest/NFU South West Scholarship Fund. These are hugely important for a sustainable dairy industry.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Dairy Crest also gives financial backing to The Prince’s </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Countryside Fund which aims to rejuvenate the rural economy and also supports the farming help charities who care for farmers in any sort of distress. We are a key partner with others in the dairy sector in The Prince’s Dairy Initiative which is working wi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">th farmers at most disadvantage to help them reduce their costs and remain in dairy farming.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Where Government can help</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">We would like to see support for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which attract the best people to work in dairying.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">There is more room for working collaborati</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">vely across sector,  for instance in The Prince’s Dairy Initiative, and with farmers, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eg</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> DCD and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Agri</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> assist, to avoid duplication, improve understanding and benefit from economies of scale.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold">Ways of increasing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold">self-sufficiency</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold"> in products for which the U</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:18pt; font-weight:bold">K has a comparative advantage</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Publicising Britain’s world-leading standards</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The dairy industry needs to be proactive in encouraging high animal welfare standards in the UK. The milk produced by our direct suppliers is 'farm </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">assured', ensuring that we use </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">only top quality milk produced to stringent standards governing food safety, animal welfare and protection of the environment.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Our direct supplying farms must comply fully with the requirements of the Assured Dairy Farm (ADF) national dairy farm assurance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> scheme. The ADF scheme focuses on all aspects of dairy husbandry and milk production.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In addition to the RTADS, Dairy Crest has introduced its own Country Life Farm Standards with additional criteria for suppliers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">focussed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on best practice. The standards </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">have been piloted on a regional group of farms and many of our farms are now working to these additional standards. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">M&amp;S</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><spa